03987nam a22006855i 9780271078168DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20112011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710781687 a10.1515/97802710781682doi  a(DE-B1597)584269  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPN3347 7aPHI0040002bisacsh04a809/.933532221 aKliger, Ilya, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Narrative Shape of Truth :bVeridiction in Modern European Literature /cIlya Kliger. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLiterature and Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliteration -- tIntroduction: The Veridictory Mutation of the Novel -- t1. Precipitant Knowledge in Balzac -- t2. The Whole and the Untrue: Stendhal's Fragile Veridiction -- t3. Enigma and Emplotment in Dostoevsky -- t4. Tolstoy's Plotlines and Truth Shapes -- tConclusion: Enduring the Schema in Modernist Time -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIts champions-and its detractors-have often understood the novel as the genre par excellence of truthlessness. The Narrative Shape of Truth counters this widely accepted view. It argues instead that the novel has found new, historically specific configurations of truth and narrative. The nineteenth-century novel, in particular, can be understood as responding to the emerging tendency to view truth as inseparable from, rather than opposed to, time. Ilya Kliger offers a nonreductive way of reading the histories of philosophy and the novel side by side. He identifies the crucial moment in the epistemological history of narrative when, at the end of the eighteenth century, a new structural affiliation between truth and time emerged. This book examines novels by four authors-Balzac, Stendhal, Dostoevsky, and Tolstoy-as well as the writings of leading European intellectuals and philosophers. Kliger argues that the "realist" novel can be conceived as prompting us (and giving us the means) to think of truth differently, as immanent in a temporal shape rather than transcendent in a principle, a fact, or a higher order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEuropean fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aFictions, Theory of. 0aLiteraturexPhilosophy. 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 0aTruth in literature. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Epistemology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271078168423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271078168.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK